  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves knowingly engaging in financial transactions to conceal the origin, ownership, or control of illegally obtained funds. It is a serious crime because it enables criminal enterprises to profit from illegal activities while making the proceeds appear legitimate.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is prosecuted under federal law (e.g., the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, codified at **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957**) and under state laws. Penalties for money laundering can include substantial fines, forfeiture of assets, and long prison sentences, often up to **20 years** per count, depending on the severity and scope of the crime.\n\nAdditionally, money laundering is often associated with other serious crimes, such as drug trafficking, terrorism financing, fraud, and organized crime, which can lead to even harsher penalties. If you are facing charges or have questions about money laundering, it\u2019s essential to consult a qualified attorney.",
